success.question_text: How tall is Edward?

stimulus_3.text:
He has named the gnomes Cyril, Cedric and Edward.

Cyril is taller than Cedric by the same amount as Cedric is taller than Edward.

Cyril is 0.83 m tall and Cedric is 0.69 m tall.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

When adding or subtracting decimals, it is best to write them under one another with the same place values and the decimal points lined up.

success.question_text: Which of the following does Aydin see?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Space / Transformations

stimulus_1.text:
Aydin writes the number 4 on a square piece of paper.

He flips the paper over its right side edge so that the blank side of the paper faces him.

He then flips it over its top side edge so that the side of the paper with the 4 faces him.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

A reflection is like painting a shape on paper and then folding the paper to produce an identical image. A reflection is often called a flip. When the two shapes are being compared, the fold line is the axis of symmetry.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Capacity and Volume

stimulus_2.text:
The container above holds 1 litre of water.

How much water will the container below hold?

review_3.column_1_text:
The volumes of the two containers are the same so they will each hold the same amount of liquid.

The second container will hold 1 litre of liquid.

Tip

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Number Patterns

review_3.column_1_text:
The differences between the numbers are increasing by 4 each time:

6 add 4 is 10 add 8 is 18 add 12 is 30 add 16 is 46 add 20 is 66.

Now add 24 to 66 to give 90.

The next number is 90.

Tip

To find a particular term in a sequence, discover the rule and then write out the terms until you arrive at your answer. If the pattern is simple, you may be able to skip terms.

success.question_text: What did Rebeckah’s paper look like when she unfolded it?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Space / Transformations

stimulus_1.text: Rebeckah folded a sheet of paper in half and then folded it in half again.

stimulus_3.text: From the bottom right corner she cut out a square.

review_3.column_1_text:
When the rectangle is folded and folded again, it is four layers of paper thick.

This means that any object cut out will be cut out four times.

When you cut a square in the corner and then open up the paper, the squares have joined into two rectangles on each side of the paper.

Tip

When paper folding, the number of layers of paper gives the number of repeated cut-out shapes.

success.question_text:
It is then folded along the dotted lines to form an open box and placed on a table with the open face up.

What is the letter on the bottom of the box?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Space / 3D Objects and Nets

stimulus_1.text:
A piece of paper is cut out into a series of joined squares as shown in the diagram below.

A different letter is printed on each square.

review_3.column_1_text:
Looking at the net you can see that face A will be opposite face C and face D will be opposite face E. There is no face opposite face B so that must be the face that is on the bottom.

When the box is constructed the square with the letter B will be on the bottom.

Tip

To find the arrangements of faces of a cube from its net, first find the faces that will be opposites on the cube. This will exclude some of the possibilities as they will be hidden from view. Finally, imagine the cube’s faces forming as the folding of the net occurs.

Practise by cutting out nets and folding the paper to form solids.

stimulus_3.text: The shape is altered by changing the position of one of the squares.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

The perimeter is the distance around the outside boundary of a shape. Sometimes the easiest way to find the perimeter is to just count the units.

success.question_text: Which numbers could be written on the unknown cards?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Number / Number Averages

stimulus_1.text:
Four numbers are written on cards.

The average of the four numbers is 6.

Two of the cards are turned over so that the numbers cannot be seen.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

A number that is halfway between two other numbers is the average of the two numbers.

To find an average, add the numbers together and divide by however many numbers have been added.

success.question_text: If the match is broadcast live in Sydney, what time will it begin?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Time

stimulus_2.text: A cricket match begins in London at 11 am on Thursday. On Thursday, London time is 10 hours behind Australian Eastern Standard Time.

review_3.column_1_text:
London time is 10 hours behind Sydney time on Thursday.

So Sydney time is 10 hours ahead of London time.

10 hours ahead of 11 am is 9 pm on the evening of the same day.

The time in Sydney will be 9 pm Thursday.

Tip:

In different places around the world, time can differ by up to 24 hours. Have a look at a map or globe that also shows time. Daylight saving time in the different countries will also affect time differences.

success.question_text: What should it have been?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Number / Operations

stimulus_2.text: Kylie wanted to add 80 but instead subtracted 80 by mistake. Her answer was 240.

review_3.column_1_text:
After subtracting 80, Kylie’s answer was 240.

Before 80 was subtracted the number was 240 + 80 = 320.

Kylie should have added 80.

320 + 80 = 400

The answer should have been 400.

Tip

Addition and subtraction are opposite or inverse operations. One undoes what the other one does.

success.question_text: The code for the word WISH is
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Algebra, Function and Patterns / Number Plane

stimulus_1.text:
A grid can be used to describe a code.

For example, the letter N is (5, 2).

review_3.column_1_text:
Using the grid, W = (3, 3), I = (0, 2), S = (7, 3) and H = (0, 1).

This means that WISH is (3, 3) (0, 2) (7, 3) (0, 1).

Tip

When breaking (or deciphering) codes, use what is known to find what is unknown.

stimulus_1.text: The graph shows the cost to hire tools from Bengarry Tool Hire for different amounts of time.

review_1.column_1_text:
Solution

If a tool is hired for more than 2 hours but less than 3 hours the cost is $100.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Learn to read information from all types of graphs. For example, this graph looks a little like a set of steps and is called a step graph.

success.question_text: Using the information from the graph, who was correct?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Graphs

stimulus_1.text: The graph shows the cost to hire tools from Bengarry Tool Hire for different amounts of time.

stimulus_3.text:
One of the owners of Bengarry Tool Hire, Ben, said: ‘It costs $20 per hour to hire a tool for 6 hours.’

The other owner of Bengarry Tool Hire, Garry, said: ‘It costs more to hire 3 tools for half an hour than to hire 1 tool for 4 hours.’

review_1.column_1_text:
Solution

Consider each statement:

‘It costs $20 per hour to hire a tool for 6 hours.’

The cost to hire a tool for 6 hours is $126.

review_6.column_1_text:
Tip

Make sure you can read the scale on a graph. For example, in this question each larger division on the vertical (Cost) axis is $20. Each larger division is divided into five smaller divisions, so each smaller division is $20 ÷ 5 = $4.

stimulus_2.text:
Bridgett worked out the volume of a cube with side 2 cm.

A new cube is formed by increasing the length of each side by 1 cm.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

The volume of a rectangular prism is length × breadth × height. In a cube each of these lengths are the same so the volume of a cube is side × side × side.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Number / Decimals

review_3.column_1_text:
You can estimate the answer to 5.32 × 2.4.

As 5.32 is close to 5 and 2.4 is close to 2, then an approximate answer is 5 × 2 = 10.

Considering the choices, 10 is closest to 12.768.

The answer to 5.32 × 2.4 is 12.768.

Tip

When two decimals are multiplied, there must be the same number of places after the decimal point in the answer as there were (in total) in the question. For example, in this question there are 2 digits after the decimal point in 5.32 and 1 after the decimal point in 2.4 so the answer must have 3 (2 + 1) digits after the decimal point.
